    "originalText": "# Spaghetti Bolognese\n\nA rich, slow-simmered meat sauce with spaghetti. Serves 4.\n\n## Ingredients\n\n### Vegetables\n- 1 large onion, finely diced\n- 2 medium carrots, finely diced\n- 2 stalks celery, finely diced\n- 4 cloves garlic, minced\n\n### Meat\n- 500 g beef mince (80/20)\n\n### Pantry\n- 400 g crushed tomatoes (one 400 g tin)\n- 70 g tomato paste (double concentrate)\n- 120 ml red wine (a dry Italian like Chianti)\n- 15 ml olive oil\n- 5 g salt\n- 2 g black pepper\n- 3 g dried oregano\n- 2 bay leaves\n\n### Pasta & Dairy\n- 400 g spaghetti\n- 50 g Parmesan, freshly grated\n\n## Equipment\n- Large heavy-bottomed pan or Dutch oven\n- Large pot for pasta\n- Cutting board and knife\n- Grater\n\n## Instructions\n\n1. **Prep the soffritto**: Finely dice the onion, carrots, and celery. Mince the garlic.\n2. **Build the base**: Heat olive oil in a large pan over medium heat. Add the diced onion, carrot, and celery. Cook for 8 minutes, stirring occasionally, until softened and lightly golden. Add the garlic and cook 1 minute more until fragrant.\n3. **Brown the meat**: Increase heat to medium-high. Add the beef mince, breaking it up with a wooden spoon. Cook for 6-8 minutes until well browned with no pink remaining. Season with salt and pepper.\n4. **Deglaze**: Pour in the red wine and scrape up any browned bits from the bottom. Let it bubble for 2 minutes until mostly evaporated.\n5. **Build the sauce**: Stir in the crushed tomatoes, tomato paste, oregano, and bay leaves. Bring to a gentle simmer.\n6. **Simmer**: Reduce heat to low, cover partially, and simmer for 30 minutes, stirring every 10 minutes. The sauce should thicken and the flavours meld together. Remove bay leaves.\n7. **Cook the pasta**: About 10 minutes before the sauce is done, bring a large pot of well-salted water to a rolling boil. Cook spaghetti according to package directions until al dente (usually 8-10 minutes). Reserve 240 ml of pasta water before draining.\n8. **Combine**: Add the drained pasta to the sauce. Toss vigorously, adding splashes of pasta water until the sauce coats the spaghetti evenly.\n9. **Serve**: Divide among warm bowls and top generously with freshly grated Parmesan. Serve immediately.\n\n## Notes\n\nFamily favourite. The soffritto (onion-carrot-celery) is the backbone — do not skip it. Kids prefer less garlic; use 2 cloves instead of 4. Leftovers keep well for 3 days in the fridge and freeze beautifully without the pasta.",
